properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Avoca River to Charlton.

  • MINOR FLOODING MAY DEVELOP AT CHARLTON TOWN FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON
  • River levels are elevated along the Avoca River catchment due to the recent rainfall and minor flooding may develop along the Avoca River at Charlton Town from Monday afternoon.
  • In the 24 hours to 12:00 pm Monday, rainfall totals of 5-10 mm were recorded in the Avoca catchment. 
  • No significant rainfall forecast for the remainder of Monday into Tuesday. 
  • The Avoca River at Charlton Township is currently at 3.90 metres and rising slowly, below the minor flood level (4.00 m). 
  • The Avoca River at Charlton Township may peak around the minor flood level (4.00 m) Monday afternoon.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 27/06/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOCKER RD BRIDGE

MINOR FLOODING EXPECTED AT WANGARATTA TUESDAY AFTERNOON

Minor flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge. Minor flooding is expected to occur along the Ovens River at Wangaratta Tuesday afternoon.

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Tuesday, rainfall totals of 5-20 mm have been recorded in the Ovens and King River catchments. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Tuesday and into Wednesday.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

King River:

Minor flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge.

The King River at Docker Rd Bridge peaked at 3.91 metres around 04:00 am Tuesday 27 June, below the moderate flood level. The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is currently at 3.90 metres and steady, above the minor flood level (3.70 m). The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is likely to remain above the minor flood level (3.70 m) during Tuesday into Wednesday.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point:

Minor flooding is expected along the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 11.82 metres and rising slowly, below the minor flood level (11.90 m). The Ovens River at Wangaratta is expected to exceed the minor flood level (11.90 m) Tuesday afternoon. The river level is likely to peak near 12.00 metres Tuesday evening and is likely to remain above the minor flood level (11.90 m) overnight Tuesday into Wednesday.


Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes. 
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • Check out the Wangaratta Local Flood Guide for more flood information and what might happen, to help you be best informed and prepared, click here: Wangaratta Local Flood Guide
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.  
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.  Be prepared to act if your situation changes. 
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams. 
  • Riverside carparks will be closed at Bickerton St, Sydney Beach and Baker St. 
  • Great Alpine Road may be closed at Yellow Creek
  • Parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds are closed due to flooding. To find out more go to www.parkweb.vic.gov.au/safety/flood-affected-parks.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded. 
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au. 
  • Water will be up to Yogi's chin in the Apex Park.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 28/06/2023 11:50 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Cape Conran, Marlo.

  • Due to a whale carcass on the beach, there could be an increase in shark activity reported at Point Ricardo.
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:

  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.
Impacts in your area:
  • Victorian Fisheries Authority is assisting wildlife officers and park rangers with the management of the whale carcass.
This message was issued by Victorian Fisheries Authority.

The next update is expected by 30/06/2023 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.   
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

MINOR FLOODING CONTINUING AT BANDIANA

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Tuesday, no significant rainfall has been recorded across the Kiewa River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for next few days.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge:

Minor flooding is occurring along the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.81 metres and steady, above the minor flood level (2.80 metres). The Kiewa River at Bandiana is likely to remain around the minor flood level (2.80 m) during Tuesday into Wednesday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
